<h2>What Is Roasting?</h2>

<p>
  Coffee roasting applies heat to green beans, triggering chemical reactions that transform them into the aromatic, flavorful product we brew. Green beans smell like grass — there's nothing coffee-like about them. Roasting creates the flavor from scratch.
</p>

<p>
  During roasting, <strong>hundreds of chemical reactions occur simultaneously</strong>: water evaporation, organic acid breakdown and formation, sugar caramelization, Maillard reactions between amino acids and sugars, lipid oxidation, chlorogenic acid degradation. Together, these reactions produce brown beans containing <strong>over 1,000 volatile aromatic compounds</strong>.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Roasting by the Numbers</h4>
  <p>
    Roasting temperature: ~180–230°C / Time: 8–20 minutes (varies by method)<br />
    Green bean moisture: 10–12% → Post-roast: 1–2.5%<br />
    Weight loss: 12–20% (moisture + volatile organic compounds)<br />
    Volume increase: 50–100% (internal gas expansion)
  </p>
</div>

<h2>The Three Phases of Roasting</h2>

<h3>1. Drying Phase</h3>

<p>
  From loading until the bean reaches ~150°C — typically 4–8 minutes. Primary activity: <strong>moisture evaporation</strong>. Bean color shifts from green to yellow. This phase looks uneventful, but it's foundational: uneven drying causes "baked" beans, where interior and exterior roast at different rates. Even drying ensures subsequent reactions develop uniformly throughout the bean.
</p>

<h3>2. Maillard Reaction Phase</h3>

<p>
  Around 150–190°C, the heart of roasting chemistry begins: the <strong>Maillard reaction</strong> — amino acids and reducing sugars react to form brown pigments (melanoidins) and an enormous variety of aromatic compounds.
</p>

<p>
  First described by French chemist Louis-Camille Maillard in 1912, this reaction is responsible for most of the "appealing brown" in food: bread crust, seared steak, dark beer. In coffee, the Maillard reaction is the <strong>single largest driver of flavor development</strong>.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>The Maillard Cascade</h4>
  <p>
    <strong>① Initial stage:</strong> Amino group (−NH₂) from amino acids condenses with carbonyl group (C=O) from reducing sugars to form Schiff bases → Amadori rearrangement → Amadori compounds.<br />
    <strong>② Intermediate stage:</strong> Amadori compounds undergo dehydration, fragmentation, and cyclization, generating reductones, furfurals, and other intermediates.<br />
    <strong>③ Final stage:</strong> Intermediates react with each other and amino acids (including Strecker degradation) → melanoidins (brown polymers) + hundreds of volatile aroma compounds.
  </p>
</div>

<h3>3. Development Phase</h3>

<p>
  At ~196°C, accumulated steam and CO₂ pressure physically crack the bean — <strong>First Crack</strong>. A popcorn-like snapping sound. This marks a pivotal transition.
</p>

<p>
  After first crack, <strong>caramelization</strong> accelerates — sugars break down into caramel-like sweetness and bitter compounds. Organic acids (especially chlorogenic acid) degrade rapidly; perceived acidity drops.
</p>

<p>
  Continuing to ~224°C brings <strong>Second Crack</strong> — cellulose in cell walls fractures, producing a finer crackling sound. Past second crack, smoky, bittersweet, dark-chocolate flavors dominate, and origin-specific character diminishes rapidly.
</p>

