<h2>Key Reactions in Detail</h2>

<h3>Strecker Degradation</h3>

<p>
  Within the Maillard cascade, <strong>Strecker degradation</strong> is particularly important for aroma. α-dicarbonyl Maillard intermediates react with amino acids, generating amino-acid-specific aldehydes called Strecker aldehydes. These form the backbone of coffee's aromatic profile:
</p>

<p>
  Leucine → <strong>3-methylbutanal</strong> (chocolate-like) / Isoleucine → <strong>2-methylbutanal</strong> (fruity) / Valine → <strong>2-methylpropanal</strong> (nutty).
</p>

<h3>Caramelization</h3>

<p>
  Unlike the Maillard reaction (which requires amino acids), <strong>caramelization</strong> proceeds with sugar alone. Sucrose melts and decomposes at ~186°C, undergoing dehydration, cyclization, and polymerization to produce hundreds of compounds — including <strong>diacetyl</strong> (buttery), <strong>furanones</strong> (caramel-like), and <strong>maltol</strong> (sweet aroma). Darker roasts mean more caramelization and increasing bittersweet character.
</p>

<h3>Chlorogenic Acid Degradation</h3>

<p>
  Green beans contain 6–10% chlorogenic acid (CGA) by dry weight. Roasting degrades most of it, especially in dark roasts. CGA breaks down into <strong>quinic acid</strong> and <strong>caffeic acid</strong>; further degradation creates <strong>phenylindanes</strong>, the primary source of dark roast's characteristic harsh bitterness.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>Acidity and Roast Level</h4>
  <p>
    Light roast coffee is "acidic" — but not just sharp or sour. Early in roasting, CGA breakdown generates organic acids (acetic, formic, lactic), temporarily increasing acidity. As roasting continues, these acids themselves degrade. So light roast coffee doesn't taste "sour" — it has <strong>complex acidity from diverse organic acids</strong>. The difference is between sharp tartness and bright, nuanced, fruit-like acidity.
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Coffee's Aromatic Compound Library</h2>

<p>
  Roasted coffee contains <strong>1,000+ identified volatile compounds</strong> — more than wine (~500) and among the highest of any food. Key categories:
</p>

