<p>
  <strong>2-Furfurylthiol</strong> deserves special attention — detectable at concentrations of just a few parts per trillion, it's considered the primary "coffee aroma" compound. Its detection threshold is so low that it dominates the scent profile even in tiny quantities.
</p>

<h2>Roast Profile Design</h2>

<p>
  Modern specialty roasters treat roasting as a function of <strong>temperature and time</strong>, monitoring drum temperature, bean surface temperature, and <strong>RoR (Rate of Rise)</strong> in real time, adjusting heat to hit a target flavor profile.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Turning Point:</strong> When beans first enter the hot drum, temperature briefly drops (cold beans absorb heat) before rising again — typically reached 1–2 minutes after loading.
</p>

<p>
  <strong>RoR (Rate of Rise):</strong> Temperature increase per unit time. A smoothly declining RoR through the roast ("downward slope") is generally considered ideal. A sudden RoR spike ("flick") or a crash followed by a spike ("crash and flick") are defect indicators.
</p>

<div class="info-box">
  <h4>DTR — Development Time Ratio</h4>
  <p>
    DTR = Time after first crack ÷ Total roast time × 100<br /><br />
    General guidelines:<br />
    <strong>15–20%:</strong> Light roast. Bright acidity, origin character pronounced.<br />
    <strong>20–25%:</strong> Medium. Balanced, sweetness well-developed.<br />
    <strong>25%+:</strong> Dark. Heavy body, dominant bitterness.<br /><br />
    DTR is a guideline, not a rule. The same DTR can produce very different cups depending on the heat curve that led there.
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Roast Level and Origin Character</h2>

<p>
  In specialty coffee, roasting serves to <strong>reveal origin character</strong>, not to override it. Lighter roasts let origin-specific acids and aromatics lead. Darker roasts increasingly express roast-derived character (chocolate, caramel, smoke), suppressing terroir flavors.
</p>

<p>
  Ethiopian Yirgacheffe's jasmine and bergamot aromatics sing brightest at <strong>light to medium-light</strong>. Brazil's nutty, chocolatey profile finds its best expression at <strong>medium to medium-dark</strong>. But "lighter is always better" is wrong too — underdeveloped roasts produce cereal-like, grassy flavors from incomplete Maillard reactions. The craft is in balancing origin expression with sufficient sweetness and body development.
</p>

<h2>Summary</h2>

<p>
  Roasting is the orchestration of Maillard reactions, caramelization, and organic acid degradation — hundreds of reactions unfolding simultaneously. The roaster's job is to understand these reactions well enough to guide them precisely toward the target: the fullest possible expression of what's inside a single green bean.
</p>

